<m:mo> / </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> s </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:math>
. Since acceleration is in the direction of motion, the particle is accelerated and the resulting displacement – time curve is a parabola with increasing slope. 
</para>
<para id="element-421">
The displacement at the end of 4 s is 5 + 10 + 25 = 40 m
</para>
<para id="element-422">Now, the displacement between times 4 and 5 s is :
</para>
<para id="element-423">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mo> Δ </m:mo>
<m:mi> x </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mfrac>
<m:mn> 1 </m:mn>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:mfrac>
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mo> x </m:mo> 
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mn> 30 </m:mn>
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mo> x </m:mo> 
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mn> 1 </m:mn>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mn> 15 </m:mn>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-424">The velocity between 2 and 4 s is decreasing at constant rate, but always remains positive. As such, the acceleration is constant, but negative and its magnitude is equal to the slope, which is <m:math>
<m:mfrac bevelled="true">
<m:mn> 30 </m:mn>
<m:mn> 1 </m:mn>
</m:mfrac>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mn> 30 </m:mn>
<m:mspace width="2pt"/>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
